<doc id="220782" wikidata="Q1754547" url="?curid=220782" title="Exterior derivative">
<text>On a differentiable manifold, the exterior derivative extends the concept of the differential of a function to differential forms of higher degree. The exterior derivative was first described in its current form by Élie Cartan in 1899. The resulting calculus, known as exterior calculus, allows for a natural, metric-independent generalization of Stokes&#x27; theorem, Gauss&#x27;s theorem, and Green&#x27;s theorem from vector calculus.

If a differential -form is thought of as measuring the flux through an infinitesimal -parallelotope at each point of the manifold, then its exterior derivative can be thought of as measuring the net flux through the boundary of a -parallelotope at each point.

== Definition ==
The exterior derivative of a differential form of degree (also differential -form, or just -form for brevity here) is a differential form of degree .

If is a smooth function (a -form), then the exterior derivative of is the differential of . That is, is the unique -form such that for every smooth vector field , , where is the directional derivative of in the direction of .

The exterior product of differential forms (denoted with the same symbol ) is defined as their pointwise exterior product.

There are a variety of equivalent definitions of the exterior derivative of a general -form.

=== In terms of axioms ===
The exterior derivative is defined to be the unique -linear mapping from -forms to -forms that has the following properties:

*The operator formula_1 applied to the formula_2-form formula_3 is the differential formula_4 of formula_3
*If formula_6 and formula_7 are two formula_8-forms, then formula_9 for any field elements formula_10
*If formula_6 is a formula_8-form and formula_7 is an formula_14-form, then formula_15 (&quot;graded product rule&quot;)
*If formula_6 is a formula_8-form, then formula_18 (Poincaré&#x27;s lemma) 

If formula_3 and formula_20 are two formula_2-forms (functions), then from the third property for the quantity formula_22, which is simply formula_23, the familiar product rule formula_24 is recovered. The third property can be generalised, for instance, if formula_6 is a formula_8-form, formula_7 is an formula_14-form and formula_29 is an formula_30-form, then

:formula_31

